<subsection xml:id="subsection-solving-triangles">
    <title>Solving Triangles</title>

    <p>Now that we have defined trigonometric functions, we can use them to analyze triangles. The goal is to find the all of the side lengths and/or angles given only some of them.</p>

    <figure xml:id="figure-triangle-generic-labels">
        <caption>Right Triangle with Labels</caption>
        <image source="images/triangle-generic" width="50%" />
    </figure>

    <example xml:id="example-triangle-solve1">
        <p>A right triangle has a leg of length 12 and the hypotenuse has length 13, what is the length of the other leg? What are the angles?</p>
        <p>We know lengths of two sides so we can apply the Pythagorean Theorem to calculate the length of the third side.
        <md>
            <mrow>12^2+b^2 &amp; = 13^2.</mrow>
            <mrow>b^2 &amp; = 13^2-12^2.</mrow>
            <mrow>b^2 &amp; = 25.</mrow>
            <mrow>b &amp; = 5.</mrow>
        </md></p>
        <p>For the angle opposite the side of length 12, we can use the inverse sine to calculate the angle. <me>\arcsin\left(\frac{12}{13}\right) \approx 67^\circ.</me></p>
        <p>For the angle opposite the side of length 5, we can use the angle sum theorem
            <md>
                <mrow>90^\circ+67^\circ+B &amp; \approx 180^\circ.</mrow>
                <mrow>B &amp; \approx 180^\circ-90^\circ-67^\circ.</mrow>
                <mrow>B &amp; \approx 23^\circ.</mrow>
            </md>
        The angle measure is approximate, because we rounded the result of the inverse sine calculation. Rounding to units here was arbitrarily chosen because we do not have a context.</p>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-triangle-solve2">
        <introduction>
            <p>A right triangle has legs of length 14 and 48.</p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>What is the length of the other side?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The other side is the hypotenuse. We can calculate it using the Pythagorean theorem.
                <md>
                    <mrow>c^2 &amp; = 14^2+48^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; 2500.</mrow>
                    <mrow>c &amp; = \sqrt{2500}</mrow>
                    <mrow> &amp; = 50.</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>What are the measures of the angles?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>For the angle opposite the side of length 14, we can use <me>\arctan\left( \frac{14}{48} \right) \approx 16^\circ.</me> We choose to use the inverse tangent (as opposed to inverse sine) because the given information was the legs.</p>
                <p>For the other angle we can use the angle sum theorem.
                <md>
                    <mrow>90^\circ+16^\circ+B &amp; \approx 180^\circ.</mrow>
                    <mrow>B &amp; \approx 180^\circ-90^\circ-16^\circ.</mrow>
                    <mrow>B &amp; \approx 74^\circ.</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </example>

    <exercise xml:id="exercise-trig-solve1">
        <myopenmath problem="1057071" />
    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="example-triangle-solve4">
        <p>For a right triangle with angle <m>\alpha=50^\circ</m> and opposite side length 7, what are the other side lengths and angles?</p>
        <p>First, we know that two of the angles are <m>90^\circ</m> and <m>50^\circ</m>, so the third angle has measure <m>180^\circ-90^\circ-50^\circ = 40^\circ</m>.</p>
        <p>To calculate the length of the hypotenuse recall that <m>sin(\alpha)=\frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}}</m>. We know the angle and the length of the opposite.
        <md>
            <mrow>\sin(50^\circ) \amp \approx 0.76604444.</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{7}{h} \amp \approx 0.76604444.</mrow>
            <mrow>7 \amp \approx h \cdot 0.76604444. \amp \text{ clearing the denominator}</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{7}{0.76604444} \amp \approx h.</mrow>
            <mrow>h \amp \approx 9.1378510.</mrow>
        </md>
        The hypotenuse has length 9.13. Now that we know two sides we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to calculate the length of the adjacent.
        <md>
            <mrow>7^2+b^2 \amp = 9.1378510^2.</mrow>
            <mrow>b^2 \amp = 9.1378510^2-7^2.</mrow>
            <mrow>b^2 \amp = 34.500321.</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt{b^2} \amp = \sqrt{34.500321}.</mrow>
            <mrow>b \amp \approx 5.8736974.</mrow>
        </md>
        The adjacent has length 5.87.</p>
    </example>

